# CASE / UCO / CAC Ontology Alignment

This project is built on a stack of interlocking open ontologies. Every data structure, export, and internal representation MUST be grounded in these ontologies to enable true interoperability with the digital investigation and Project VIC communities, and to ensure court-defensible, scientifically rigorous output.

## The Ontology Stack

| Layer | Ontology | What It Covers | Where to Find It |
|-------|----------|----------------|-------------------|
| Foundation | **UCO** — Unified Cyber Ontology | Core cyber-domain concepts (files, accounts, devices, identities, locations, time) | https://unifiedcyberontology.org/ · https://github.com/ucoProject |
| Investigation | **CASE** — Cyber-investigation Analysis Standard Expression | Investigations, investigative actions, evidence, provenance, chain of custody | https://caseontology.org/ · https://github.com/casework |
| Domain | **CAC Ontology** — Crimes Against Children Ontology | Grooming, exploitation indicators, victim/offender modeling, Project VIC categories, analyst wellbeing | https://site.cacontology.projectvic.org/ · https://github.com/Project-VIC-International/CAC-Ontology |
| Forensic Science (optional but encouraged) | **SOLVE-IT** | Forensic techniques, weaknesses, mitigations, tool profiles, ASTM E3016-18 error categories | https://ontology.solveit-df.org/ · https://github.com/SOLVE-IT-DF/solve-it-ontology |

Use UCO/CASE/CAC at minimum. Add SOLVE-IT when your tool performs a documented forensic analysis whose error modes need to be defensible in court (carving, hashing, perceptual hashing, AI classification, OCR, timeline reconstruction, etc.). For CAC tools that may end up cited in trial exhibits, **SOLVE-IT alignment is strongly recommended.**

## Why Each Ontology Matters in Plain Language

- **UCO** is the dictionary. Every cyber thing — a file, an account, a phone number, an IP address — has a UCO class with a stable IRI. Without UCO, two agencies cannot agree on what the word "file" means in machine-readable form.
- **CASE** is the grammar of an investigation. It connects observations to the actions that produced them, ties evidence to chain-of-custody actors, and gives every assertion a provenance trail.
- **CAC Ontology** speaks the specific vocabulary of Crimes Against Children work. It defines categories like grooming stages, Project VIC CSAM categorization, victim age estimation, and analyst wellbeing exposures. It is the layer that lets a CAC investigator's tool output be understood by another CAC investigator's tool.
- **SOLVE-IT** is the layer that makes your output **defensible**. It catalogues the known weaknesses of every forensic technique, the mitigations that address them, and the ASTM E3016-18 error categories that defense counsel will ask about on cross-examination. A SOLVE-IT-aligned tool tells the court not just "we found this," but "we found this using technique T, which has weakness W, which we mitigated with M, and the residual error category is E."

## Tools the Agent Must Use

### CASE/UCO/CAC SDKs

Project VIC and the CASE community publish SDKs in multiple languages (Python, Rust, Java, C#) that provide typed builders for all CASE/UCO/CAC classes. These SDKs enforce required fields, produce correct `@context`, and are the **authoritative way to emit JSON-LD** — much more reliable than hand-writing JSON.

